ce:section.ce:para:
The interaction between the CDs and solvents not only enabled turn-on FL emission, but also brought out color changes due to emission wavelength shift (Fig. 6e). As expected, CDs@MIL-101 nano-sensor exhibited sensitive visual detection based on changes of PL intensity and wavelength shift. To investigate the visual detection mechanism of CDs@MIL-101, the emission maxima (λ

                           max
                        ) of the solvents as a function of solvent polarity were shown in Fig. 6f. It was clear that the scatter plot for the whole solvents showed no relevant rules through analysis. Obviously, these spots in Fig. 6f exhibited a linear relationship in two separated lines (red dash line and blue dash line). Through analysis and comparison, it was discovered that these spots in the red dash line coincidentally possessed no hydrogen-bonding donor acidity (α = 0, as seen in Table S3). It was found that the solvent polarity mainly determined the PL emission wavelength (λ

                           max
                        ) and represented the linear relationship. When α was not equal to 0, these spots were located in the blue dashed line with different slopes compared to these spots having no α. Thus, solvent polarity and hydrogen donation capacity worked together on their responded PL emission wavelength (λ

                           max). By comparison, the blue line exhibited a lower slope than the red one, indicating that the influence of hydrogen-bonding donor acidity (α) was obviously smaller than the solvent polarity on the red-shift of PL emission (λ

                           max
                        ) for water detection.
